{"title_page": "Keigo Higashino", "text_new": "{{Japanese name|Higashino}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name        = Keigo Higashino\n|image       =\n|caption     = \n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1958|2|4}}\n|birth_place = [[Ikuno-ku, Osaka]], [[Osaka Prefecture]], Japan\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|nationality = Japanese\n|occupation  = [[Author]]\n|period= 1985\u2013present\n|genre= [[Mystery fiction]], [[crime fiction]], [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]]\n|alma_mater         = [[Osaka Prefecture University]]\n|education = Osaka Prefectural Hannan High School\n|notableworks = {{Unbulleted list|''[[Naoko]]''||''[[The Devotion of Suspect X]]''|''[[Miracles of the Namiya General Store]]''}}\n|awards = {{Unbulleted list|[[Edogawa Rampo Prize]]|[[Mystery Writers of Japan Award]]|[[Honkaku Mystery Award]]|[[Naoki Prize]]|[[Chuokoron-Shinsha|Ch\u016b\u014dk\u014dron Prize]]}}\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Keigo Higashino'''|\u6771\u91ce \u572d\u543e|Higashino Keigo|extra=born February 4, 1958}} is a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[author]] chiefly known for his [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] novels. He served as the 13th President of [[Mystery Writers of Japan]] from 2009 to 2013. Higashino has won major Japanese awards for his books, almost twenty of which have been turned into films and TV series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bookbrowse.com/biographies/index.cfm/author_number/2206/keigo-higashino|title=Keigo Higashino author biography|last=BookBrowse|website=BookBrowse.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHigashino was born in the [[Ikuno-ku, Osaka|Ikuno-ku]] ward of the city of [[Osaka]] in [[Osaka Prefecture]]. The [[Logogram|logographic]] letters that make up the family name were initially read as \"Tono\", but Keigo's father changed the reading to \"Higashino\".\n\nGrowing up in a working class area, Higashino's childhood was challenging because of the lower class to which his family belonged.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.vertical-inc.com/books/naoko.html|title=Naoko \u2014 Vertical, Inc.|website=www.vertical-inc.com|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> He attended Koji Elementary School, Higashi Ikuno Junior High School, and Hannan High School. During his high school years he started reading [[mystery fiction]].\n\nHigashino studied [[Electrical Engineering]] at [[Osaka Prefecture University]], where he became captain of the [[archery]] club. He graduated with a [[Bachelor of Engineering]] degree.\n\n== Career ==\nHigashino started writing while in high school and university, showing his manuscripts to friends.\n\nIn 1981 he began working as an engineer at Nippon Denso Co''.'' (presently [[Denso|DENSO]]), and married a high school teacher. He continued to write in the evenings and on weekends,<ref name=\":2\" /> submitting unpublished mystery novels for consideration for the annual [[Edogawa Rampo Prize]] in 1983. In 1984 his submission, which drew on his wife's occupation, reached the final round. In 1985, at the age of 27, he won the Rampo Prize for best unpublished mystery for ''H\u014dkago'' (\u653e\u8ab2\u5f8c, ''After School''), drawing on experiences of the archery club at his former university. He resigned from DENSO in 1986 to start a career in [[Tokyo]] as a full-time writer.\n\nIn 1998 Higashino published ''Himitsu'' (\u79d8\u5bc6, ''Secret''), which was converted into a feature film and won the 52nd [[Mystery Writers of Japan Award]] for feature films in 1999. ''Secret'' was later translated into English by Kerim Yasar and published as ''[[Naoko (novel)|Naoko]]'' in 2004, with a limited print run.<ref name=\":2\" /> Higashino was inspired to write the story by reading a book in which a young child possessed the memories of someone who died nearby. He tried writing a short story featuring the implications of what would happen in such an instance, \"but the ideas didn\u2019t fully materialize. Finally I presented it as a novel and it got picked up.\" A 1999 Japanese film, ''[[Himitsu (film)|Himitsu]],'' was based on the book, as was a 2007 English-language French remake,''[[The Secret (2007 film)|The Secret]]''',''''' starring [[David Duchovny]].<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nIn 2006 Higashino won the 134th [[Naoki Prize]] for ''Y\u014dgisha Ekkusu no Kenshin'' (''\u5bb9\u7591\u8005X\u306e\u732e\u8eab, [[The Devotion of Suspect X]])'', an award for which he'd been nominated five times previously. ''Suspect X'' also won the 6th [[Honkaku Mystery Award]] and was ranked the number-one novel by ''[[Kono Mystery ga Sugoi!#2006|Kono Mystery ga Sugoi! 2006]]'' and ''[[Honkaku Mystery Best 10#2006|2006 Honkaku Mystery Best 10]]'', annual mystery fiction guide books published in Japan. The English edition of ''Suspect X'', translated by [[Alexander O. Smith]], was nominated for the 2012 [[Edgar Award]] for Best Novel and the 2012 [[Barry Award (for crime novels)|Barry Award]] for Best First Novel.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nHigashino received the Eiji Yoshikawa Literary Prize in 2014 for {{nihongo|''Inori no Maku ga Oriru Toki''|\u7948\u308a\u306e\u5e55\u304c\u4e0b\u308a\u308b\u6642|}}, ''When the Curtain of Prayer Descends''), the 10th book<ref>Kaga appears in 9 novels as well as the short story collection ''Uso o M\u014d Hitotsu Dake'' (\u5618\u3092\u3082\u3046\u3072\u3068\u3064\u3060\u3051, ''Just One More Lie''), 2000.</ref> to feature Detective Kyoichiro Kaga. He thought that the book was the end of the Kaga series, as he had done what he wanted to do with it.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://book.asahi.com/booknews/update/2014031100005.html|title=\u300c\u30c0\u30d6\u30eb\u53d7\u8cde\u300d\u306b\u5927\u6ca2\u30fb\u6771\u91ce\u4e21\u6c0f\u8a9e\u308b\u3000\u5409\u5ddd\u82f1\u6cbb\u6587\u5b66\u8cde [Osawa and Higashino talk about \"double award\" @ Eiji Yoshikawa Literary Prize]|last=|first=|date=March 11, 2014|website=|language=ja|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222051744/http://book.asahi.com/booknews/update/2014031100005.html|archive-date=December 22, 2017|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHigashino is one of the most popular authors in Asia and, reportedly, the most popular novelist in China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/books/article/2178736/best-books-2018-haruki-murakami-keigo-higashino-and-if|title=The best books of 2018 - ones that made us laugh and cry|last=Kidd|first=James|date=2018-12-19|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> Translation rights for his books, like ''Suspect X,'' were sold as far afield as China, Thailand, France, Russia and Spain.<ref name=\":2\" /> Both his ''The Devotion of Suspect X'' and ''[[Salvation of a Saint]]'' were published in 6 languages.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-no2002-58147/|title=Higashino, Keigo 1958-|last=|first=|date=2020|website=WorldCat Identities|access-date=January 8, 2020}}</ref> His popularity has drawn the attention of Asian academics, with papers and master's theses on his work published in China,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globethesis.com/?t=2355330542957618|title=Acceptance And Dissemination Of Higashino Keigo In China (2007-2017)|last=Li|first=RJ|date=March 17, 2019|website=Globe Thesis|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106065840/https://www.globethesis.com/?t=2355330542957618|archive-date=January 6, 2020|access-date=January 6, 2020}}</ref> Indonesia,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Endah Adriana|first=Ajeng|last2=Andry Anita Dewi|first2=Ni Made|date=November 1, 2018|title=Penggunaan Tindak Tutur Dan Implikatur Pada Novel Yougisha X no Kenshin karya Keigo Higashino [The Usage of Speech Acts and Implicatur in Yougisha X no Kenshin novel by Keigo Higashino]|url=https://ojs.unud.ac.id/index.php/sastra/article/view/43113|journal=Humanis|language=Indonesian|volume=22, 4|pages=860\u2013867|doi=10.24843/JH.2018.v22.i04.p04|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref> Malaysia,<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Art of Murder: a Comparative Study of the Crime Writing of Thomas de Quincey and Keigo Higashino. Dissertation submitted in partial fulfilment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Arts|last=Jie|first=Koik Shuh|publisher=Universiti Sains Malaysia|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and Taiwan,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.airitilibrary.com/Publication/alDetailedMesh?docid=U0002-2101201615124400|title=A study of the detective of \"Kyoichiro Kaga\" by Keigo Higashino. Tamgang University Japanese Literature Scholarship Thesis|last=Weifen|first=Zhang|date=January 1, 2016|website=Airiti Library|language=ja|access-date=January 6, 2020}}</ref> for example, but has also stimulated United States scholars.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hawley|first=John C|date=2017|title=Khaled Hosseini, Keigo Higashino, and Zoe Ferraris: Social Concealment, Personal Revelation, and Community Guilt|url=https://scholarcommons.scu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1151&context=engl|journal=The Delhi University Journal of the Humanities and the Social Sciences|volume=4|pages=1\u201318|via=}}</ref> \n\nHigashino was elected president of the [[Mystery Writers of Japan]] in 2009, and served until 2013. From 2002 to 2007 he served on various MWJ selection committees, and fulfilled a similar role for the Edogawa Rampo Award from 2008 to 2013. In 2014 he became a selection member for the Naoki Prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://book.asahi.com/booknews/update/2013102400001.html|title=\u76f4\u6728\u8cde\u9078\u8003\u59d4\u54e1\u306b\u9ad8\u6751\u85ab\u6c0f\u3068\u6771\u91ce\u572d\u543e\u6c0f\u3000\u6765\u5e74\u9078\u8003\u4f1a\u304b\u3089 - \u672c\u306e\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc [Kaoru Takamura and Keigo Higashino selected as members of the Naoki Prize Selection Committee]|last=|first=|date=2014-03-22|website=Book.asahi.com|language=ja|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322043231/http://book.asahi.com/booknews/update/2013102400001.html|archive-date=March 22, 2014|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mystery.or.jp/member/detail/0371|title=\u4f1a\u54e1\u540d\u7c3f, \u73fe\u4f1a\u54e1 - \u6771\u91ce\u3000\u572d\u543e [Current Members, Higashino Keigo]|last=|first=|date=2013|website=Mystery Writers of Japan, Inc.|language=ja|access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami|Great East Japan Earthquake]] of 2011, Higashino donated the royalties of 100,000 copies of the reprint of ''Kirin no Tsubasa'' (\u9e92\u9e9f\u306e\u7ffc, ''[[The Wings of the Kirin]]),'' the sequel to ''Newcomer'', to relief efforts in affected areas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sponichi.co.jp/society/news/2011/03/18/kiji/K20110318000451400.html|title=\u6771\u91ce\u572d\u543e\u3055\u3093\u300c\u9e92\u9e9f\u306e\u7ffc\u300d\u5897\u5237\u5206\u306e\u5370\u7a0e\u3092\u5bc4\u4ed8 [Keigo Higashino donates royalties for reprint of \"Kirin no Tsubasa\"]|last=|first=|date=March 18, 2011|website=Sponichi.co.jp|language=ja|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924190704/http://www.sponichi.co.jp/society/news/2011/03/18/kiji/K20110318000451400.html|archive-date=September 24, 2015|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\nHigashino reportedly avoids publicity as he prefers people not to recognize him on the street.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Contents and style ==\nHigashino admitted in 2015 that his content and style had changed from his earlier writings, in which he treated motivation as the most important element.<ref name=\":0\" /> In a 2011 interview he stated that he wants his \"readers to be continually surprised by my ideas.\u201d<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://blogs.wsj.com/scene/2011/02/11/is-this-guy-the-next-steig-larsson/|title=Is this Guy the Next Stieg Larsson?|last=Joyce|first=Andrew|date=February 11, 2011|work=The Wall Street Journal - Scene Asia|access-date=January 5, 2020|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110214065222/http://blogs.wsj.com/scene/2011/02/11/is-this-guy-the-next-steig-larsson/|archive-date=February 14, 2011}}</ref> \n\nIn addition to mystery novels, Higashino writes essays and story books for children. His style of writing the latter differs from his novels, and he does not use as many characters as in his novels.{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}} Higashino's works often include scientific elements, such as nuclear power generation and brain transplantation. Sports references, such as archery and [[kendo]], ski jumping, and snowboarding, also occur often. \n\nAs can be expected, Japanese elements suffuse his novels; for example, in ''Suspect X'' a major character works at a [[bento]] lunch shop, while a murder is committed with the electrical cord from a [[kotatsu]]. ''Suspect X'' inverts the classical [[whodunit]] structure, as the reader learns early on who the murderer is. Andrew Joyce writes in ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' that Hagashino explores how \"feelings of loyalty and the oppressive weight of human relations\" are \"catalysts for murder and dark pacts between neighbors or co-workers to dispose of bodies.\" Higashino claims that Japanese people prefer this format, in which the effects of characters' actions and intentions, in terms of emotions such as guilt and anguish, become clearer only towards the end of the story.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWhile Higashino admits to liking Western writers, he feels most strongly influenced by Japanese authors such as [[Edogawa Ranpo|Edogawa Rampo]] and [[Seich\u014d Matsumoto|Seicho Matsumoto]]. And \"so my work naturally has that Japanese sense of old-fashioned loyalty and concern for human feeling.\u201d With regards his Western readers, Higashino wants them \"to read my work and come to understand how Japanese people think, love and hate. I want them to be impressed that there is a Japanese person who came up with such unusual stories.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Works in English translation==\n===Novels===\n;[[Detective Galileo]] series\n*''[[The Devotion of Suspect X]]'' (original title: ''Y\u014dgisha X no Kenshin''), trans. Alexander O. Smith ([[St. Martin's Press|Minotaur Books]], 2011)<ref>{{cite book|author=Higashino, Keigo|title=The Devotion of Suspect X|translator=Alexander O. Smith|series=Detective Galileo Series|volume=1|year=2011|pages=320|isbn=9781250002693}}</ref>\n*''[[Salvation of a Saint]]'' (original title: ''Seijo no Ky\u016bsai''), trans. Alexander O. Smith (Minotaur Books, 2012)<ref>{{cite book|author=Higashino, Keigo|title=Salvation of a Saint|series=Detective Galileo Series|translator=Alexander O. Smith|publisher=Minotaur Books|year=2012|volume=2|pages=336|isbn=978-1250036278}}</ref>\n*''A Midsummer's Equation'' (original title: ''Manatsu no H\u014dteishiki''), trans. Alexander O. Smith (Minotaur Books, 2016)<ref>{{cite book|title=A Midsummer's Equation|author=Higashino, Keigo|publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]]/[[Macmillan Publishers]]|translator=Alexander O. Smith|series=Detective Galileo Series|year=2016|volume=3|pages=[https://archive.org/details/midsummersequati0000higa/page/368 368]|isbn=9781250027924|url=https://archive.org/details/midsummersequati0000higa/page/368}}</ref>\n;Police Detective Kaga series\n*''Malice'' (original title: ''Akui''), trans. Alexander O. Smith (Minotaur Books, 2014)<ref>{{cite book|author=Higashino, Keigo|title=Malice|translator=Alexander O. Smith|publisher=Minotaur Books|origyear=2014|year=2015|edition=2nd|pages=288|isbn=978-1250070326}}</ref>\n*''Newcomer'' (original title: ''Shinzanmono''), trans. Giles Murray (Minotaur Books, 2018)<ref>{{cite book|author=Higashino, Keigo|title=Newcomer|translator=Giles Murray|publisher=Minotaur Books|year=2018|pages=352|isbn=9781250067869}}</ref>\n;Other novels\n*''[[Naoko (novel)|Naoko]]'' (original title: ''Himitsu''), trans. Kerim Yasar ([[Vertical (company)|Vertical]], 2004)<ref>{{cite book|author=Higashino, Keigo|title=Naoko|publisher=[[Vertical (company)|Vertical]]|translator=Kerim Yasar|year=2004|pages=288|isbn=1932234071}}</ref>\n*''[[Journey Under the Midnight Sun]]'' (original title: ''Byakuyak\u014d''), trans. Alexander O. Smith ([[Little, Brown Book Group|Hachette]], 2015)<ref>{{cite book|author=Higashino, Keigo|title=Under the Midnight Sun|translator=Alexander O. Smith|publisher=Hachette|year=2015|isbn=978-0349138749}}</ref>\n*''The Name of the Game is a Kidnapping'' (original title: ''G\u0113mu no Na wa Y\u016bkai''), trans. Jan Mitsuko Cash (Vertical, 2017)<ref>{{cite book|author=Higashino, Keigo|title=The Name of the Game is a Kidnapping|publisher=[[Penguin Random House]]|year=2017|pages=240|isbn=978-1942993834}}</ref>\n*''The Miracles of the Namiya General Store'' (original title: ''Namiya Zakkaten no Kiseki''), trans. Sam Bett (Yen On, 2019)<ref>{{cite book|author=Higashino, Keigo|title=The Miracles of the Namiya General Store|publisher=Yen On|year=2019|pages=320|isbn=978-1975382575}}</ref>\n\n===Essay===\n*My Favourite Mystery: ''Kuroi gash\u016b'' (\u9ed2\u3044\u753b\u96c6, ''The Black Art Book'') by Seich\u014d Matsumoto (Mystery Writers of Japan, Inc.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mystery.or.jp/en/column.html?id=favorite-2|title=My Favourite Mystery #2: Kuroi gashu (The Black Art Book) (author: Matsumoto Seicho). Translated by Adrian Pinnington.|last=Higashino|first=Keigo|date=2010|website=Mystery Writers of Japan|access-date=January 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" |List of accolades received by Keigo Higashino\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Award \n! Recipients and Nominees\n! Result\n|-\n|1983\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Edogawa Rampo Award]]\n| ''Ningy\u014d-tachi no ie'' (''Dolls' House'')\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|1984\n| ''[[:ja:\u9b54\u7403 (\u5c0f\u8aac)|Maky\u016b]]'' (''Magic Ball)''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[:ja:\u653e\u8ab2\u5f8c (\u6771\u91ce\u572d\u543e)|H\u014dkago]]'' (''After School'')\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|1988\n|Eiji Yoshikawa Pr