l cities: 454, an increase of 20 compared with the 1989 census.<ref name=cen2001/>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|Administrative divisions development in Ukraine|Ukrainian historical regions}}\n\nBefore the introduction of oblasts in 1932, Ukraine comprised 40 [[Okruhas of Ukriane|okruha]]s, which had replaced the former [[Russian Empire|Russian Imperial]] [[guberniya]] (governorate) subdivisions.\n\nIn 1932 the territory of the Ukrainian SSR was re-established based on oblasts. Excluded in the administrative changes was [[Western Ukraine]], which at that time formed part of the [[Second Polish Republic]] and shared in the Polish form of administrative division based on [[Voivodeships of Poland|voivodeships]].\n\nIn the post-[[World War II]] period, the [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic]] consisted of [[Administrative divisions of the Ukrainian SSR|25 oblasts and two cities with special status]].\n\nAfter the fall of the Soviet Union in 1991, Crimea obtained the status of an autonomous republic with its own government instead of a regional state administration.\n\n==Regions==\n{{Ukraine Labelled Map|float=right}}\n\n===Autonomous republic===\n{{Main|Autonomous Republic of Crimea}}\n\nThe Autonomous Republic of Crimea, formerly the Crimean Oblast of the Ukrainian SSR, geographically encompasses the major portion of the Crimean peninsula in southern [[Ukraine]]. Its capital is [[Simferopol]]. The Autonomous Republic of Crimea is the only region within Ukraine that possesses its own constitution.\n\nOn March 16, 2014, after the occupation of Crimea by the Russian military, a referendum on joining the Russian Federation was conducted. A majority of votes supported the measure. On March 21, 2014, the Russian Duma voted to annex Crimea as a [[Republic of Crimea|subject]] into the Russian Federation. The Ukrainian government does not recognize the referendum or annexation of Crimea as legitimate. On March 27, the UN General Assembly passed [[United Nations General Assembly Resolution 68/262|Resolution 68/262]] by 100 to 11 votes, recognizing the referendum as invalid and denying any legal change in the status of Crimea and Sevastopol.\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ddd; vertical-align:top;\"\n! Autonomous Republic of Crimea\n! [[Representatives of the President of Ukraine]]\n! Area (km<sup>2</sup>)\n! Population (2010)\n! Pop. density\n! Administrative centre\n! Raions/Districts\n! Cities of regional significance {{#tag:ref|\"[[City of regional significance (Ukraine)|cities of regional significance]]\" is a translation of {{lang-uk|\u041c\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f}}.|group=\"nb\"}}\n|-\n|{{flag|Crimea}}\n|Nataliya Popovych\n|26,100\n|1,966,801\n|75\n|[[Simferopol]]<ref>temporarily in [[Kherson]]</ref>\n|14\n|11\n|-\n|}\n\n===Oblasts===\n{{Main|Oblasts of Ukraine}}\n\nOblasts are on the first (top) level of the administrative division of Ukraine.\n \nAlmost every oblast is named after its administrative center, except for four oblasts. Volyn' and Zakarpattia, whose respective capitals are Lutsk and Uzhhorod, are named after historic regions [[Volhynia]] and [[Carpathian Ruthenia|Transcarpathia]]. The administrative centers of the Dnipropetrovsk Oblast and the Kirovohrad Oblast were renamed to Dnipro and Kropyvnytskyi in 2016, however as of 2017 the oblasts still officially bear the old soviet names as their change must be reflected in an amendment to the Ukrainian Constitution. \n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ddd; vertical-align:top;\"\n! Region\n! Area (km<sup>2</sup>)\n! Population (2010)\n! Pop. density\n! Administrative center\n! Raions/Districts\n! Cities of regional significance {{#tag:ref|\"[[City of regional significance (Ukraine)|cities of regional significance]]\" is a translation of {{lang-uk|\u041c\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f}}.|group=\"nb\"}}\n|-\n|{{flag|Cherkasy Oblast}}\n|20,891\n|1,291,135\n|61.80\n|[[Cherkasy]]\n|20\n|6\n|-\n|{{flag|Chernihiv Oblast}}\n|31,851.3\n|1,104,241\n|34.67\n|[[Chernihiv]]\n|22\n|3\n|-\n|{{flag|Chernivtsi Oblast}}\n|8,093.6\n|903,782\n|111.67\n|[[Chernivtsi]]\n|11\n|2\n|-\n|{{flag|Dnipropetrovsk Oblast}}\n|31,900.5\n|3,344,073\n|104.83\n|[[Dnipro]]\n|22\n|13\n|-\n|{{flag|Donetsk Oblast}}\n|26,505.7\n|4,448,031\n|167.81\n|[[Donetsk]]\n|18\n|28\n|-\n|{{flag|Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast}}\n|13,894.0\n|1,380,770\n|99.38\n|[[Ivano-Frankivsk]]\n|14\n|6\n|-\n|{{flag|Kharkiv Oblast}}\n|31,401.6\n|2,755,177\n|87.74\n|[[Kharkiv]]\n|27\n|7\n|-\n|{{flag|Kherson Oblast}}\n|28,449\n|1,091,151\n|38.35\n|[[Kherson]]\n|18\n|3\n|-\n|{{flag|Khmelnytskyi Oblast}}\n|20,636.2\n|1,331,534\n|64.52\n|[[Khmelnytskyi, Ukraine|Khmelnytskyi]]\n|20\n|6\n|-\n|{{flag|Kyiv Oblast}}\n|28,118.9\n|1,719,602\n|61.15\n|[[Kiev|Kyiv]]\n|25\n|13\n|-\n|{{flag|Kirovohrad Oblast}}\n|24,577.5\n|1,014,809\n|41.29\n|[[Kropyvnytskyi]]\n|21\n|4\n|-\n|{{flag|Luhansk Oblast}}\n|26,672.5\n|2,300,412\n|86.25\n|[[Luhansk]]\n|18\n|14\n|-\n|{{flag|Lviv Oblast}}\n|21,823.7\n|2,545,634\n|116.65\n|[[Lviv]]\n|20\n|9\n|-\n|{{flag|Mykolaiv Oblast}}\n|24,587.4\n|1,186,452\n|48.25\n|[[Mykolaiv]]\n|19\n|5\n|-\n|{{flag|Odessa Oblast|Odesa Oblast}}\n|33,295.9\n|2,387,636\n|71.71\n|[[Odessa]]\n|26\n|7\n|-\n|{{flag|Poltava Oblast}}\n|28,735.8\n|1,493,668\n|51.98\n|[[Poltava]]\n|25\n|5\n|-\n|{{flag|Rivne Oblast}}\n|20,038.5\n|1,152,576\n|57.52\n|[[Rivne]]\n|16\n|4\n|-\n|{{flag|Sumy Oblast}}\n|23,823.9\n|1,166,765\n|48.97\n|[[Sumy]]\n|18\n|7\n|-\n|{{flag|Ternopil Oblast}}\n|13,817.1\n|1,086,694\n|78.65\n|[[Ternopil]]\n|17\n|1\n|-\n|{{flag|Vinnytsia Oblast}}\n|26,501.6\n|1,646,250\n|62.12\n|[[Vinnytsia]]\n|27\n|6\n|-\n|{{flag|Volyn Oblast}} \n|20,135.3\n|1,038,223\n|51.56\n|[[Lutsk]]\n|16\n|4\n|-\n|{{flag|Zakarpattia Oblast}} \n|12,771.5\n|1,246,323\n|97.59\n|[[Uzhhorod]]\n|13\n|5\n|-\n|{{flag|Zaporizhia Oblast}}\n|27,168.5\n|1,805,431\n|66.45\n|[[Zaporizhia]]\n|20\n|5\n|-\n|{{flag|Zhytomyr Oblast}}\n|29,819.2\n|1,283,201\n|43.03\n|[[Zhytomyr]]\n|23\n|5\n|}\n\n===Cities with special status===\n{{Main|Cities with special status}}\n\nTwo cities carry special status: the city of [[Kyiv]] which is the capital of Ukraine and the city of [[Sevastopol]]. Following the [[2014 Crimean crisis]], Sevastopol is controlled by Russia and is incorporated as a [[Federal subjects of Russia|federal subject of Russia]]. It is recognized as a part of Ukraine by most of the international community.\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ddd; vertical-align:top;\"\n!City\n! [[Chief of Local State Administration (Ukraine)|Governor]]{{#tag:ref|Chairman of the Regional (or City) State Administration.|group=\"nb\"}}\n! Area\n! Population (2010)\n|-\n|{{flag|Kyiv}}\n|[[Vitali Klitschko]]{{#tag:ref|[[Vitaliy Klychko]] serves both as a mayor and a governor for the city of Kiev since 25 June 2014 (see [[Mayor of Kyiv]]).|group=\"nb\"}}\n|{{convert|323.9|sqmi|km2|order=flip|abbr=on}}\n|2,782,016\n|-\n|{{flag|Sevastopol}}\n|''[[Governor of Sevastopol (Ukraine)|vacant]]''\n|{{convert|416.6|sqmi|km2|order=flip|abbr=on}}\n|380,301\n|-\n|}\n\n==Second-level subdivision units==\n\n===Cities of regional significance (regional cities)===\n{{Main|City of regional significance (Ukraine)}}\n\n===Raions===\n{{Main|Raions of Ukraine}}\n[[Raions of Ukraine|Raions]] are smaller territorial units of subdivision in Ukraine. There are 490 raions.\n\n===Urban districts===\n{{Main|Urban districts of Ukraine}}\n\n==Councils==\n{{details|Populated places in Ukraine}}\n[[File:Dniepr river in Kyiv.jpg|thumb|The [[Dnieper River]] plays an important part in Ukrainian territorial division, with many large cities settled on its banks. Here, the capital city of [[Kiev|Kyiv]] which was founded on the Dnieper's right bank but for now expanded over the river significantly.]]\n\n{| border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=2 style=\"text-align:left; border:1px solid #ddd; font-size:90%;\" summary=\"\"\n|- style=\"background:#ddd; vertical-align:top;\"\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=2 | Status<ref>{{cite web|title=Regions of Ukraine and their composition |url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/z7502/a002 |work=[[Verkhovna Rada|Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine]] |accessdate=25 December 2011 |language=Ukrainian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111226134808/http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/z7502/a002 |archivedate=26 December 2011 }}</ref>\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" | Status (in [[Ukrainian Language|Ukrainian]])\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{nowrap|Total Number (in 2006)}}\n|- style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"\n|colspan=2|'''[[city|misto / city]]''' || \u043c\u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e || style=\"text-align:right;\" | '''457'''\n|-\n|&nbsp; || municipality|| \u043c\u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0437\u0456 \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u0456\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u043c \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0441\u043e\u043c || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 2\n|-\n|&nbsp; || misto \u043eblastnoho znachennia || \u043c\u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 176\n|-\n|&nbsp; || misto raionnoho znachennia || \u043c\u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 279\n|- style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"\n|colspan=2|'''[[urban-type settlement|selyshche miskoho typu / town]]''' || \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0435 \u043c\u0456\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0442\u0438\u043f\u0443 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | '''886'''\n|- style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"\n|colspan=2|'''[[village|selo / village]]''' || \u0441\u0456\u043b\u044c\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | '''28,552'''\n|-\n|&nbsp; || selysche || \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0435 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1,364\n|-\n|&nbsp; || selo || \u0441\u0435\u043b\u043e || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 27,188\n|}\n\nUkraine has two types of settlements: rural and urban. Rural populated areas (\u0441\u0456\u043b\u044c\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442) can be either a village (\u0441\u0435\u043b\u043e, [[Village#Slavic countries|selo]]) or a rural settlement (\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0435). Urban populated areas (\u043c\u0456\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442) can be either a city (\u043c\u0456\u0441\u0442o) or an [[urban-type settlement]] (\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0435 \u043c\u0456\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0442\u0438\u043f\u0443). For the sake of brevity, urbanized settlements are sometimes classified as towns in the [[English language]].\n\nChanges to a settlement's status can be made only by the [[Verkhovna Rada]]. Please note that the size of a settlement does not ultimately define its status, although is a major factor. For example, the city of [[Prypiat (city)|Prypiat]] still retains its status, while having a population of zero, due to its infrastructure, including buildings, roads, and utility networks.\n\nThe typical Ukrainian ''misto'' ought to be considered a [[city]], not a [[town]] (compare to [[City status in the United Kingdom]]). However, the city's subordination to either an oblast or raion also should be taken into account, especially in the [[political]] sense. Some of urbanized settlements may be cities of raion subordination, although it could seem confusing, a type of settlement should be considered first as its status is given for administrative purposes.\n\n===Cities===\n{{see also|List of cities in Ukraine}}\n[[File:Kyiv province location map.svg|thumb|left|[[Kiev Oblast|Kyiv Oblast]] for instance, has several regional city municipalities such as [[Pereiaslav]], for example, that are under direct subordination to the regional authorities. They are officially known as cities of regional significance.]]\n[[File:Drohobycz ulica stryjska 2008.jpg|thumb|[[Drohobych]], is a city of oblast subordinance, subordinate to the [[Lviv Oblast]] authorities rather than to the local [[Drohobych Raion]] administration.]]\nAccording to Ukrainian law a city (\u043c\u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e) in Ukraine is a locality of at least 10,000 people.<ref name=UCSMBS>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QcoodEOmnMUC&pg=PA151&dq=Ukraine+city+10,000+people&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=v1fvU5b8LcSIOMPDgfgO&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Ukraine%20city%2010%2C000%20people&f=false A Geography of Russia and Its Neighbors] by Mikhail S. Blinnikov, [[Guilford Press]], 2010, {{ISBN|1606239201}} (page 151)</ref> Cities may carry various status. Some may be of national importance, others of [[city of regional significance (Ukraine)|regional (oblast) importance]], and the rest of district (raion) importance. For example, the cities of ''Kyiv'' and of ''Sevastopol'' have special status of national significance and each is officially classified as a ''city with a special status'', which administratively is equivalent to an oblast. Mayors of those cities, in general, as are governors of oblasts, are appointed by the [[President of Ukraine]]. However, the status of the mayor of Kyiv is somewhat more complex, and for further information see [[Legal status and local government of Kiev|Legal status and local government of Kyiv]]. The status of Sevastopol is also unique.\n\nAlmost every oblast has at least one city of regional subordination (importance), which is the administrative center (capital) of that oblast. However, some other big cities within the oblast may have such status as well. The cities of oblast subordination have the same importance of a raion, and often are the administrative centers of such. In addition to regular raions, several Ukrainian cities with national or oblast status are further divided into ''city raions'' which may include other cities, towns, and/or villages. In 2010, Ukraine had 23 such cities with their own city raions.\n\nMany '''raions''' also have city municipalities of its level of subordination (importance). Those are usually the administrative centers (capitals). Notice that not all raions have a city as their administrative center; however all the raion centers are at least urban-like (urbanized). All administrative centers have their own form of self-administration. The municipalities of a raion subordination may administer several adjacent local councils (municipalities), usually rural. If a raion has several cities of raion (district) level, they may share administrative power for the raion.\n\n===Other municipalities===\nIn addition to city municipalities, Ukraine has urban-like municipalities. The lowest form of self-administration are the rural municipalities and villages. A rural municipality may consist of a single village, usually big, or a combination of other rural villages or localities. Note that some villages also have some additional, very small settlements. Those settlements, together with the home village, combine a local (rural) municipality (silrada). For simplicity's sake, a silrada (rural municipality) is usually referred to as a village and is the lowest level of administrative division. The status of any settlement is granted by the [[Verkhovna Rada]].\n\n===Amalgamated hromadas (AHs)===\nIn his draft [[Ukraine's constitution|constitutional]] amendments of June 2014 [[Ukrainian President]] [[Petro Poroshenko]] proposed changing the administrative divisions of Ukraine, which should include regions, districts and \"hromadas\".<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/211043.html Poroshenko suggests granting status of regions to Crimea, Kyiv, Sevastopol, creating new political subdivision of 'community'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701043549/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/211043.html |date=2014-07-01 }}, [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (26 June 2014)</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2015, the law \"On voluntary association of territorial communities\" was adopted creating ''Amalgamated hromadas (communities)'' meaning [[Settlement council (Ukraine)|settlement councils]], [[Rural council (Ukraine)|rural councils]] and a [[City of district significance (Ukraine)|city of district significance]] can create a new administrative unit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reformsguide.org.ua/reforms/decentralizationreform/|title=Decentralization|date=2017-02-10|website=The Reforms Guide|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> Any amalgamated hromada with a city as an administrative centre is an urban hromada, any amalgamated hromada with an urban-type settlement as an administrative centre is a settlement hromada, and any amalgamated hromada with a village as an administrative centre is a rural hromada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decentralization.gov.ua/en/glossary|title=Glossary|date=|website=Decentralization Reform|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> New local [[elections in Ukraine|elections]] in these united territorial communities were then held.<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/472770.html Batkivschyna party says it gets most votes at local elections], [[Interfax Ukraine]] (25 December 2017)<br>[https://www.unian.info/politics/2316594-police-investigate-voter-bribing-cases-as-local-elections-held-in-51-territorial-communities.html Police investigate voter bribing cases as local elections held in 51 territorial communities], [[UNIAN]] (25 December 2017)</ref> 226 will be holding elections in 2018 and 2019.<ref>[http://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/ukrainealert/elections-are-around-the-corner-and-ukraine-s-political-parties-are-not-ready-2 Elections Are Around the Corner, and Ukraine\u2019s Political Parties Are Not Ready], [[Atlantic Council]] (6 December 2017)</ref> The first 252 were held in 2017.<ref>[https://www.oporaua.org/en/elections/45055-interim-report-on-observation-results-of-the-first-local-elections-in-united-territorial-communities-on-29-october-2017-19102017-26102017 INTERIM REPORT ON OBSERVATION RESULTS OF THE FIRST LOCAL ELECTIONS IN UNITED TERRITORIAL COMMUNITIES ON 29 October 2017 (19.10.2017 26.10.2017)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228223135/https://www.oporaua.org/en/elections/45055-interim-report-on-observation-results-of-the-first-local-elections-in-united-territorial-communities-on-29-october-2017-19102017-26102017 |date=28 December 2018 }}, [[PORA#OPORA|OPORA]] (31 October 2017)<br>[https://www.oporaua.org/en/elections/45165-ukraine-holds-elections-in-51-utcs-today Ukraine holds elections in 51 UTCs today] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226020921/https://www.oporaua.org/en/elections/45165-ukraine-holds-elections-in-51-utcs-today |date=2017-12-26 }}, [[PORA#OPORA|OPORA]] (24 December 2017)</ref> \n\nThe Law \"On Local Self-Government in Ukraine\" stipulates that local budgets should have enough money to be administered by local self-government bodies.<ref name=\"Espresogr\"/> Because many of the small rural councils and cities of district significance could never hope to do this the new administrative unit ''Amalgamated hromada'' ([https://uk.wikipedia.org/wiki/%D0%9E%D0%B1%27%D1%94%D0%B4%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B0_%D1%82%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%BE%D1%80%D1%96%D0%B0%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%BD%D0%B0_%D0%B3%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%BC%D0%B0%D0%B4%D0%B0]{{lang-uk|\u041e\u0431'\u0454\u0434\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0434\u0430}}, ''Obyednana terytorial\u02b9na hromada'') was created.<ref name=\"Espresogr\">{{in lang|uk}} [https://espreso.tv/article/2017/10/30/vybory_v_obyednanykh_terytorialnykh_gromadakh_scho_ce_i_dlya_chogo_potribne Elections in the united territorial communities. What is this and what you need], [[Espreso TV]] (31 October 2017)</ref>\n\n==Other administrations==\n\nUkraine also has several settlements known as ''viiskove mistechko'' which were former military installations. Since the fall of the Soviet Union, the secrecy of such settlements has been unveiled, however, the towns are subordinated directly to the Ministry of Defense and do not have their own civil administrations. Such military installations are like ghost towns that are not even identified on a map. One of them, on the border of the [[Kiev Oblast|Kyiv]] and [[Zhytomyr Oblast]]s is Makarov-1.<ref>{{cite news|title=In Kiev region a military installation cannot vote|url=http://podrobnosti.ua/video/podrobnosti/2010/10/31/727577.html|accessdate=8 February 2012|newspaper=[[Podrobnosti.ua]]|language=Russian|date=31 October 2012|format=Video|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404114906/http://podrobnosti.ua/video/podrobnosti/2010/10/31/727577.html|archive-date=2012-04-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nA special territory known as the ''[[zone of alienation]]'' falls under the jurisdiction of the Ministry of Emergencies and was the most severely affected territory by the [[Chernobyl disaster]]. Additionally, various restricted nature preserves known as ''[[Zapovednik]]'' fall under the jurisdiction of the Ministry of Ecology. \n\nDue to the [[War in Donbass]], the status of [[Civil\u2013military administrations (Ukraine)|civil\u2013military administrations]] was created in territories of [[Donetsk Oblast|Donetsk]] and [[Luhansk Oblast|Luhansk]] oblasts where the respective local government units cannot exercise their constitutionally guaranteed powers.<ref name=pravda>{{cite news|title=Poroshenko gave the green light to create civil-military administrations|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2015/02/26/7059870/|accessdate=26 February 2015|work=[[Ukrayinska Pravda]]|date=26 February 2015|location=Ukrainian}}</ref>\n\n[[File:1201044 original (1).jpg|thumb|A mix of modern and old buildings in [[Dnipro]], located in [[Dnipropetrovsk Oblast]]. Dnipro's metropolitan area includes cities such as [[Kamianske]] and [[Novomoskovsk, Ukraine|Novomoskovsk]].]]\n\nCurrently, Ukraine has the following 3 enclaves:\n*The city of [[Slavutych]] which is administratively subordinated directly to [[Kiev Oblast|Kyiv Oblast]] while being completely surrounded by neighboring [[Chernihiv Oblast]].\n*The settlement of Bile which is located on [[Snake Island (Black Sea)|Snake Island]] and is fully surrounded by the [[Black Sea]] was established in 2007 and is part of [[Vylkove]], [[Odessa Oblast]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Selysche Bile, Odessa Oblast, Kiliya Raion, city Vylkove|url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/z7502/A005?rdat1=08.02.2012&rf7571=42441|work=Regions of Ukraine and their Structure|publisher=[[Verkhovna Rada|Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine]]|accessdate=8 February 2012|language=Ukrainian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303033059/http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/z7502/A005?rdat1=08.02.2012&rf7571=42441|archive-date=2014-03-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*The town of [[Kotsiubynske]] which is part of the Kyiv Oblast and is completely surrounded by the city of Kyiv.\n\n===Metropolitan areas===\nUkraine has five major agglomerated metropolitan areas ([[conurbation]]s). These conurbation areas are not officially recognized and remain to be administered according to official [[oblast]]-[[raion]] system of subdivision.\n*[[Kiev metropolitan area|Kyiv]] includes towns such as [[Irpin]], [[Boryspil]], and [[Fastiv]]\n*Kharkiv includes towns such as [[Chuhuiv]], [[Merefa]], and numerous other settlements\n*Donetsk includes towns such as [[Makiivka]], [[Khartsyzk]], and others\n*Dnipro with [[Kamianske]] and [[Novomoskovsk, Ukraine|Novomoskovsk]]\n*Odessa with [[Chornomorsk]] and [[Ovidiopol]]\n\n==Other divisions==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=May 2016}} \n[[File:Ukraine KIIS-Regional-division2.png|thumb|Kiev International Institute of Sociology (KIIS) geographic division of Ukraine used in their polls.]]\nBeside the administrative divisions, geographical divisions are at times used for reference or statistical purposes. The division splits Ukraine into 4 to 6 geographic areas: [[Western Ukraine]], [[Eastern Ukraine]], [[Southern Ukraine]], [[Central Ukraine]], [[Northern Ukraine]] (occasionally used).\n\nThe neighboring countries such as Russia, Poland, Hungary and Romania sometimes identify certain parts of Ukraine. For example, Russia has territorial claims to Ukraine stating that the Southeastern Ukraine is part of Russia,{{fact|date=March 2017}} certain political or public figures in Poland lay territorial claims to [[western Ukraine]] identifying them as ''Borderlands'' or ''Kreis'' (Kresy),{{fact|date=March 2017}} the same goes for Hungary that calls [[Zakarpattia Oblast]] as K\u00e1rp\u00e1talja.{{fact|date=March 2017}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ukraine}}\n* [[Geography of Ukraine]]\n* [[ISO 3166-2:UA]]\n* [[List_of_places_named_after_people#Ukraine|List of places named after people (Ukraine)]]\n* [[Local government in Ukraine]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Atlas of Ukraine}}\n*{{cite web|title=Regions of Ukraine and their composition |url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/z7502/a002 |work=[[Verkhovna Rada|Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine]] |accessdate=25 December 2011 |language=Ukrainian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111226134808/http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/z7502/a002 |archivedate=26 December 2011 }}\n*{{cite web|title=Ukraine Raions|url=http://www.statoids.com/yua.html|work=Statoids|accessdate=8 February 2012}}\n*{{cite web|title=Ukrainian cities and regions in alphabetical order|url=http://ukrainetrek.com/regions-by-alphabet|work=UkraineTrek|accessdate=10 February 2012}}\n* {{cite web|title=Administrative territorial composition of Ukraine|url=http://www.minregion.gov.ua/attachments/content-attachments/1659/ATU.pdf|work=Ministry of Regional Development, Construction, and Communal Living|accessdate=5 April 2015}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{Ukraine topics}}\n{{Administrative divisions of Ukraine}}\n{{Administrative divisions of Ukraine's regions}}\n{{Articles on first-level administrative divisions of European countries}}\n\n[[Category:Subdivisions of Ukraine| ]]\n[[Category:Country subdivisions in Europe|Ukraine]]\n", "name_user": "XTOC6", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated spelling (per official UA government site: rada.gov.ua/en)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Administrative_divisions_of_Ukraine"}
{"title_page": "David Carty", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=David Carty|timestamp=20200422205503|year=2020|month=April|day=22|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=David Carty|date=22 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{short description|English football player}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = David Carty\n| image = https://images.app.goo.gl/na9NFCB1bzSXK4eM8\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Carty signing with [[Institute F.C.|Institute]] in 2020.\n| fullname = David Carty\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1994|3|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Uxbridge Road]], [[London]], [[UK]]\n| height = {{height|ft=6|in=4}}\n| position =  [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|Attacking midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Institute F.C.|Institute F.C.]]\n| clubnumber = 40\n| years1 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs1 = [[Havant & Waterlooville F.C.|Havant & Waterlooville]]\n| years2 = 2019\n| clubs2 = [[Tooting & Mitcham United F.C.|Tooting & Mitcham Utd]]\n| years3 = 2019-2020\n| clubs3 =  [[Institute F.C.|Institute F.C.]]\n}}\n'''David Carty''' (born 9 March 1994) is a [[Association football|professional football player]] from London who plays for [[Institute F.C.|Institute]] in the [[NIFL Premiership]]. He is of [[English people|English]] and [[Irish people|Irish]] descent.\n\n\n===Early life===\n\nCarty grew up on a west London estate and fell in love with football from a young age but was more focused on studies. He mainly played cage football and [[Sunday league football]] during his adolescent years. Carty has a strong Christian faith. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://kick-offsportsgroup.com/latest-news|title=Carty Turns Pro|publisher=Kick-Off Sports Group|date=19 April 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Havant & Waterlooville===\n[[Vanarama National League]] side Havant spotted Carty\u2019s raw talent and brought him into the club. He made his debut in the Hampshire Senior Cup on 11 December 2018, assisting two goals in the process. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ansfc.co.uk/item.php?pg=matchesplayed&pd=1009&sort=sdate&order=desc&fply=3&fsea=all&frt=rescomp&it=31|title=Matches for 1st team|website=ANSFC|accessdate=12 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Tooting & Mitcham United===\n\nSeeking more minutes, David moved closer to home, to south London side Tooting & Mitcham. He scored on his debut in a Isthmian League game away at title challengers Bracknell Town. <ref>{{cite web|url= http://tooting.localnewsie.co.uk/mobile#postDetail11955|title=Tooting & Mitcham United March 2019 Review|website=Tooting Localnewsie|accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Institute===\n\nCarty signed for [[Irish Premiership]] club [[Institute F.C.|Institute]], making his debut in a Danske Bank Premiership Match against Glentoran on the 18 January 2020. <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51340405|title=Making sense of the craziest transfer window in Irish Premiership history|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://overtheturnstile.uk/columnist/glens-go-top-of-the-league-against-stute-as-title-rivals-slip-up-elsewhere|title=Glens go top|website=Over The Turnstile|accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\nhttps://g.co/kgs/Pta6yp\n\nhttps://www.fieldoo.com/carty\n\nhttps://www.nifootballleague.com/danske-bank-premiership/clubs/institute/squad\n\nhttps://institutefc.co.uk/\n\nhttps://www.extratime.ie/player/11135516/david_carty/\n\nhttps://www.derryjournal.com/sport/football/sean-connor-concedes-institute-are-in-a-dog-fight-with-warrenpoint-town-1-9215053\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carty, David}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=David Carty|timestamp=20200422205503|year=2020|month=April|day=22|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=David Carty|date=22 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{short description|English football player}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = David Carty\n| image = https://images.app.goo.gl/na9NFCB1bzSXK4eM8\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Carty signing with [[Institute F.C.|Institute]] in 2020.\n| fullname = David Carty\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1994|3|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Uxbridge Road]], [[London]], [[UK]]\n| height = {{height|ft=6|in=4}}\n| position =  [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|Attacking midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Institute F.C.|Institute F.C.]]\n| clubnumber = 40\n| years1 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs1 = [[Havant & Waterlooville F.C.|Havant & Waterlooville]]\n| years2 = 2019\n| clubs2 = [[Tooting & Mitcham United F.C.|Tooting & Mitcham Utd]]\n| years3 = 2019-2020\n| clubs3 =  [[Institute F.C.|Institute F.C.]]\n}}\n'''David Carty''' (born 9 March 1994) is a [[Association football|professional football player]] from London who plays for [[Institute F.C.|Institute]] in the [[NIFL Premiership]]. He is of [[English people|English]] and [[Irish people|Irish]] descent.\n\n\n===Early Life===\n\nCarty grew up on a west London estate and fell in love with football from a young age but was more focused on studies. He mainly played cage football and [[Sunday league football]] during his adolescent years. Carty has a strong Christian faith. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://kick-offsportsgroup.com/latest-news|title=Carty Turns Pro|publisher=Kick-Off Sports Group|date=19 April 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n==Club Career==\n\n===Havant & Waterlooville===\n[[Vanarama National League]] side Havant spotted Carty\u2019s raw talent and brought him into the club. He made his debut in the Hampshire Senior Cup on 11 December 2018, assisting two goals in the process. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ansfc.co.uk/item.php?pg=matchesplayed&pd=1009&sort=sdate&order=desc&fply=3&fsea=all&frt=rescomp&it=31|title=Matches for 1st team|website=ANSFC|accessdate=12 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Tooting & Mitcham United===\n\nSeeking more minutes, David moved closer to home, to south London side Tooting & Mitcham. He scored on his debut in a Isthmian League game away at title challengers Bracknell Town. <ref>{{cite web|url= http://tooting.localnewsie.co.uk/mobile#postDetail11955|title=Tooting & Mitcham United March 2019 Review|website=Tooting Localnewsie|accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Institute===\n\nCarty signed for [[Irish Premiership]] club [[Institute F.C.|Institute]], making his debut in a Danske Bank Premiership Match against Glentoran on the 18 January 2020. <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51340405|title=Making sense of the craziest transfer window in Irish Premiership history|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://overtheturnstile.uk/columnist/glens-go-top-of-the-league-against-stute-as-title-rivals-slip-up-elsewhere|title=Glens go top|website=Over The Turnstile|accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\nhttps://g.co/kgs/Pta6yp\n\nhttps://www.fieldoo.com/carty\n\nhttps://www.nifootballleague.com/danske-bank-premiership/clubs/institute/squad\n\nhttps://institutefc.co.uk/\n\nhttps://www.extratime.ie/player/11135516/david_carty/\n\nhttps://www.derryjournal.com/sport/football/sean-connor-concedes-institute-are-in-a-dog-fight-with-warrenpoint-town-1-9215053\n\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "DB1729", "label": "safe", "comment": "default sort", "url_pa